{{about|the philosopher|the Roman physician, pharmacologist and botanist|Pedanius Dioscorides}}
'''Dioscorides''' ({{lang-grc-gre|Διοσκορίδης}}, fl. 225 BC), sometimes known as '''Dioscurides''', was a [[stoicism|Stoic]] philosopher, the father of [[Zeno of Tarsus]] and a pupil of [[Chrysippus]]. All other information has been lost.
Another '''Dioscorides''' is mentioned by [[Diogenes Laërtius]]. This philosopher was a [[pyrrhonism|Pyrrhonist]], and was a student of [[Timon of Phlius]]<ref>http://www.classicpersuasion.org/pw/diogenes/dltimon.htm</ref>
==Dedication== Chrysippus dedicated the following works to Dioscorides: *Four books on Probable Conjunctive Reasons<ref>[http://www.attalus.org/old/diogenes7d.html#190 ''The Lives of the Philosophers'' by Diogenes Laertius. Book: Lives of Stoic Philosophers, Section 190]</ref> *Five books on the Art of Reasoning and of Modes<ref>[http://www.attalus.org/old/diogenes7d.html#193 ''The Lives of the Philosophers'' by Diogenes Laertius. Book: Lives of Stoic Philosophers, Section 193]</ref> *A solution, according to the principles of the ancients, of the [[law of non-contradiction]]<ref>[http://www.attalus.org/old/diogenes7d.html#197 ''The Lives of the Philosophers'' by Diogenes Laertius. Book: Lives of Stoic Philosophers, Section 197]</ref> *Five volumes of Dialectic Arguments, with no solution<ref>[http://www.attalus.org/old/diogenes7d.html#198 ''The Lives of the Philosophers'' by Diogenes Laertius. Book: Lives of Stoic Philosophers, Section 198]</ref> *Two books on Probable Arguments bearing on Definitions<ref>[http://www.attalus.org/old/diogenes7d.html#200 ''The Lives of the Philosophers'' by Diogenes Laertius. Book: Lives of Stoic Philosophers, Section 200]</ref> *An essay on [[Rhetoric]], spanning four books<ref>[http://www.attalus.org/old/diogenes7d.html#202 ''The Lives of the Philosophers'' by Diogenes Laertius. Book: Lives of Stoic Philosophers, Section 202]</ref>
