'''Tim Dean''' is a British philosopher, author, notable in the field of contemporary [[queer theory]],<ref>{{cite book|title=Henry James and queer modernity|year=2003|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-81394-5|pages=14|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SRWfbGDJVAcC&pg=PA14 |author= Eric L. Haralson|accessdate=17 December 2010}}</ref><ref name=downing>{{cite journal|last=Downing|first=Lisa|title=Beyond Sexuality: Review|journal=Archives of Sexual Behavior|volume=34|issue=2|pages=255–263|doi=10.1007/s10508-005-1802-1|url=http://www.springerlink.com/content/q362541466343524/|accessdate=17 December 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last= Rickard|first=G Keilan|url=http://www.palgrave-journals.com/pcs/journal/v14/n1/full/pcs200815a.html|title=The land of big queers: A fairy's tale (To be read aloud then discarded just as quickly)|journal=Psychoanalysis, Culture & Society |year=2009|volume=14|pages=89–99|doi=10.1057/pcs.2008.15 |accessdate=17 December 2010}}</ref> and author of several works on the subject: ''Gary Snyder and the American Unconscious'' (1991), ''Beyond Sexuality'' (2000),<ref name=downing/> and ''Unlimited Intimacy: Reflections on the Subculture of Barebacking'' (2009),<ref>{{cite web|title=On Bareback Subcultures and the Pornography of Risk |url=http://slought.org/content/11332/|publisher=[[Slought Foundation]]|accessdate=17 December 2010}}</ref> all published by the University of Chicago Press, and a co-editor of ''Homosexuality and Psychoanalysis'' (2001).
Dean first became a British civil servant before attending the [[University of East Anglia]], during which time he participated in a Junior Year Abroad program at [[Brandeis University]], and wrote his undergraduate dissertation on [[Gary Snyder]] before graduating BA with First Class Honours in American Studies.<ref>https://illinois.academia.edu/TimDean/CurriculumVitae</ref> He subsequently earned his PhD at [[Johns Hopkins University]] (doctoral dissertation on [[Hart Crane]]). He was a Fellow at the [[Stanford Humanities Center]] (1997-1998).<ref>{{cite web|title=Fellows Update|url=http://shc.stanford.edu/intellectual-life/news/fellows-update-0|publisher=Stanford Humanities Center|accessdate=17 December 2010|date=26 February 2010|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100705085334/http://shc.stanford.edu/intellectual-life/news/fellows-update-0|archivedate=5 July 2010|df=}}</ref> He teaches at the [[University of Illinois]] ([[Urbana-Champaign]]).
