{{korean name|[[Yi (Korean name)|Yi]]}} {{unreferenced|date=February 2012}} {{Infobox Korean name | hangul=이제현 | hanja=李齊賢 | rr = I Jehyeon | mr=I Chehyŏn | hangulho = 익재, 역옹, 실재 | hanjaho = 益齋, 櫟翁, 實齋 | rrho = Ikjae, Yeogong, Siljae | mrho = Ikchae, Yŏgong, Silchae | hangulja = 지공 | hanjaja = 之公 | rrja = Jigong | mrja = Chigong | hangulph=문충 | hanjaph=文忠 | rrph=Munchung | mrph=Munch'ung }}
'''Yi Jehyeon''' ([[Korea]]n: 이제현, [[hanja]]: 李齊賢, 1287–1367) was a politician and early [[Korea]]n [[Confucianism|Neo-Confucianism]] scholar and philosopher, writer, and poet. His first name was '''Jigong''' ([[Korea]]n:지공, [[hanja]]:之公). A pen name was Ikjae (익재, 益齋)·Yeogong (역옹, 櫟翁)·Shiljae (실재, 實齋), [[courtesy name]] was Jungsa (중사, 仲思). He was a follower and successor of [[Baek Yijeong]] (백이정, 白頤正), and was the father of [[Hye-bi Yi|Hyebi Yi]], who was a concubine of [[Gongmin of Goryeo]].
